Grobots (SDL/WASM port)

This is the SDL3 and WebAssembly port of Grobots, a programming game originally
by Devon and Warren Schudy. It builds with Meson and Ninja, and targets Linux
(SDL3), WebAssembly (Emscripten), and Windows (Wine/MinGW cross-compilation).

----- About Grobots -----

Grobots is a real-time strategy programming game, in which you write programs
to control teams of robots as they forage, reproduce and fight.

The programs that control the robots are called sides, and are written in a
simple dialect of Forth. There are many sides to play with, and tournament
results to ponder.

More information at <http://grobots.sourceforge.net/>.

Grobots is free software licensed under the GNU General Public License.
(See <http://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl.html>.)

----- Building on Linux -----

To build Grobots on Linux or other Unix-like systems, you will need Meson and
Ninja. See <https://mesonbuild.com/Getting-meson.html> for installation
instructions.

1) Enter the top-level source directory.
$ cd ./source

2) Configure the build directory.
$ meson setup build

3) Build the executable.
$ ninja -C build

The headless executable will be at build/grobots_headless. If SDL3 and its
dependencies are available, the graphical build (grobots_sdl) will also be
built.

----- Building with Nix -----

If you have Nix with flakes enabled, you can build directly:

$ nix build              # graphical (SDL3) build
$ nix build .#emcc       # Emscripten/WebAssembly build
$ nix build .#wine       # Wine build
$ nix build .#mingw32    # MinGW cross-compile

Or enter a development shell with all dependencies available:

$ nix develop
$ meson setup build
$ ninja -C build

----- Building under other environments -----

Porting headless mode to other environments should be easy. Tell your
compiler to define HEADLESS as 1.

If you can build Grobots in another environment, we want your diffs
and makefiles (or local equivalent).

See <http://grobots.sourceforge.net/source.html> for info on porting
Grobots to other platforms. We are interested in portability patches,
even incomplete ones.


Have fun.

